# Git Commits

When creating git commits in this repository:

- Author must be **Sujay Davalgi** / **sujaydavalgi** (`sujay@davalgi.com` or `sujaydavalgi@users.noreply.github.com`).
- **Never** add `Co-authored-by: Cursor <cursoragent@cursor.com>` or any Cursor/agent co-author trailer.
- **Never** add any `Co-authored-by` line unless the user explicitly requests a specific human co-author.
- Keep commit messages clean: summary + body only, no agent attribution footers.

## Logical chunks

**Always commit in logically separate chunks** — never one large catch-all commit when the work spans distinct features.

Split by cohesive unit of change, for example:
- One feature or phase per commit (e.g. `verify` block, then `observe` fusion, then scheduler)
- Rust core vs TypeScript mirror for the same feature can be one commit if they are inseparable; otherwise split
- Tests and examples with the feature they cover, not in a separate "misc tests" commit
- Refactors or unrelated fixes in their own commits

Before committing, use `git status` and `git diff` to group related files. Stage and commit each group separately with a focused message. Push only when the user asks (or after all chunks are committed, if they said to push).

If a session produced many unrelated changes, prefer multiple commits over squashing everything into one.

If a commit message would include a Cursor co-author trailer, omit it entirely.
